"{\"uid\": \"skynews.com.au-australia-news-sport-rest-today-conquer-tomorrow-gold-medallist-spotted-sleeping-in-a-park-after-complaining-about-the-beds-in-the-paris-olympic-village-news-story-83ab6d72b6af52bba8bceb3367b7f64c\", \"text\": \"A gold medallist has been seen sleeping next to a park bench outside his designated accommodation in the Paris Olympic village, after complaining about the lack of air-conditioning and the level of noise.  Italian swimming champion Thomas Ceccon has been spotted sleeping on the grass outside his Olympic Village accomodation after complaining about the uncomfortable beds and lack of air-conditioning.  Ceccon won gold for Italy in the 100m backstroke final on day three of the competition before failing to reach the 200m backstroke final on Wednesday.  The image of Ceccon sleeping outside followed the Olympian complained about the rough beds, lack of air conditioning and disappointing food, and admitting he struggled between the \\\"heat and the noise\\\" at the designated athlete village in Paris.  Since athletes may choose to stay elsewhere if they desire, Ceccon's makeshift bed outside the Olympic Village indicated that he left his dormitory in search of a more comfortable sleeping arrangement.  Husein Alireza, a member of the Saudi Arabian rowing team, posted a video on Instagram of Ceccon sleeping next to a park bench within the Olympic Village compound in Saint Denis.  The video is captioned \\\"rest today, conquer tomorrow\\\", with Ceccon seen sleeping soundly on a white towel with his shoes and bag neatly placed beside him.  Ceccon told The Sun there was no air conditioning in the village and that it was hot and the food was \\\"bad\\\".  Italy's Swimmer, Thomas Ceccon sleeping outside because he was fed up with no A/C in the Olympic village. Bro, got his rest and locked\\u00f0\\u0178\\u00a5\\u2021pic.twitter.com/YIjjG3lwFo  \\\"Many athletes move for this reason: it's not an alibi or an excuse, it's the reality of what perhaps not everybody knows,\\\" Ceccon said.  \\\"I am disappointed that I did not make the final, but I was too tired. It's hard to sleep both at night and in the afternoon. Here, I really struggle between the heat and the noise.\\\"  The broader Italian team has reportedly declined to add any further comment.  Speaking to Fox League host Matty Johns in Paris, former Australian Olympic swimmerJames Magnussen spoke on their podcast last week about the \\\"fatigue\\\" athletes were grappling with in Paris.  \\\"Firstly, there is the fatigue factor. She (Mollie O'Callaghan) races night one, 4 x 100 relay - gold medal, sky high emotionally. Then you have to come back down that next day to swim the heats of the 200m freestyle, very hard to do,\\\" Magnussen said.  It came after organisers of the Paris Olympic village were lambasted for the poor living conditions athletes faced, with Magnussen telling Johns many athletes would \\\"miss out\\\" on a medal due to being \\\"unsettled by this new environment\\\".  The discontent has been so severe the American tennis team has left the Olympic Village for a nearby hotel.  \\\"We have not seen this at an Olympic Games before. We have not had this amount of complaints about a village in Olympics history,\\\" Magnussen said.  To join the conversation, pleaselog in.Do not have an account?Register  Join the conversation, you are commenting asLogout  Our Apps\"}"